1
00:00:01,752 --> 00:00:29,986
namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sampuddhasa namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sampuddhasa namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sampuddhasa

2
00:00:29,966 --> 00:00:35,320
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:54,554 --> 00:00:56,816
There's always this blank when I begin a talk.

4
00:00:59,598 --> 00:01:00,399
Starts somewhere.

5
00:01:03,323 --> 00:01:11,171
I suppose what I'd like to do is make a link between what we're doing in meditation and what we do in the world out there.

6
00:01:13,894 --> 00:01:15,534
And people find that difficult.

7
00:01:16,436 --> 00:01:17,837
I was rather fortunate.

8
00:01:18,397 --> 00:01:24,004
When I say people find it difficult, I mean people in this particular tradition, especially Theravada.

9
00:01:25,182 --> 00:01:38,123
also in other traditions, but I always feel sort of fortunate because I began with Zen Buddhism up in North England, the Throstle Hole Abbey Foundation, I don't know whether you know of it.

10
00:01:39,724 --> 00:01:47,578
And Zen practice is very much based on

11
00:01:48,655 --> 00:02:16,062
work you do a lot of work physical work I'm now talking about the monastic routine up there obviously when they do a special course of just meditation there tends to be more meditation they call it a session but just in their ordinary daily rota they do a lot of work physical work you know they keep gardens

12
00:02:18,305 --> 00:02:29,347
And this came about because of the history of Buddhism in China which then spread to Japan where the idea of begging was just not on.

13
00:02:30,348 --> 00:02:38,305
And so the Chinese monks began to grow their own food, things like that.

14
00:02:40,192 --> 00:02:59,516
The reason you worked hard, I mean you put a lot of energy into it, was because in the work you got your concentration and your mindfulness so that when you went to sit there was that attention, there was the ability to watch.

15
00:03:02,449 --> 00:03:17,176
So that mixture of working, even though it was physical work, and meditation, made it quite easy for me to see how the meditation worked in daily life, how it just moved into it.

16
00:03:17,396 --> 00:03:22,306
There was no real thought about it, it just went into daily life.

17
00:03:23,228 --> 00:03:25,352
Whatever you were doing, you attended to it.

18
00:03:27,508 --> 00:03:37,045
And one thing that helps, of course, is the way that Zen or Chan or Dzogchen, some of you might know Dzogchen from the Tibetan tradition, begin their meditation.

19
00:03:39,789 --> 00:03:43,836
You might describe it as awareness at the six sense doors.

20
00:03:45,741 --> 00:03:52,352
In Buddhism you have the five senses, which we're all aware of, and the sixth sense, which is the mind itself.

21
00:03:52,331 --> 00:03:54,776
It's a sensing thing, it receives.

22
00:03:55,195 --> 00:03:58,020
It receives thoughts, it receives emotions.

23
00:04:00,304 --> 00:04:12,723
And being, so we say, at the forefront, within the all, it's easy to maintain that sort of general awareness when you go out into the world.

24
00:04:13,324 --> 00:04:16,769
So there didn't seem to be this huge distinction.

25
00:04:20,497 --> 00:04:22,661
Now I just used the word there, the all.

26
00:04:23,021 --> 00:04:23,882
That's the Buddha, you see.

27
00:04:24,083 --> 00:04:24,963
He says the all.

28
00:04:25,485 --> 00:04:27,228
The six senses is the all.

29
00:04:29,271 --> 00:04:39,588
So to understand that, we have to get the idea that we are actually living in this bubble, this bubble of consciousness.

30
00:04:40,470 --> 00:04:41,391
It doesn't have

31
00:04:41,759 --> 00:04:44,103
an edge to it which is contained.

32
00:04:44,182 --> 00:04:45,144
It's just this space.

33
00:04:45,665 --> 00:04:51,036
So at this present time, in terms of my eye consciousness, I'm just caught within this room.

34
00:04:51,136 --> 00:04:53,360
It's difficult for me to see outside this room.

35
00:04:54,182 --> 00:04:59,531
So visually, I'm caught within the bubble, you might say, of this visual consciousness.

36
00:05:01,415 --> 00:05:03,278
And that's all I know, isn't it?

37
00:05:05,384 --> 00:05:34,463
and it's a sort of truism all you know is what you know you can't go beyond what you know and what you know is that which the senses give you and your own mind and your own heart there's nothing else you can't go beyond that so in a sense we're living in this enclosed little universe of my consciousness consciousness

38
00:05:35,776 --> 00:05:39,002
And it's obviously similar, but different from yours.

39
00:05:40,324 --> 00:05:41,466
Otherwise we couldn't communicate.

40
00:05:43,589 --> 00:05:51,423
But walking into this room, nobody will deny that the room has, as it were, its own existence, for want of a better word.

41
00:05:52,285 --> 00:05:54,569
So if we all leave, nobody believes the room disappears.

42
00:05:54,848 --> 00:05:56,072
It's not here because we see it.

43
00:05:57,173 --> 00:06:00,939
But on the other hand, thinking subjectively,

44
00:06:02,117 --> 00:06:09,908
this room, there exist as many rooms as there are people in it, in terms of how the room is experienced.

45
00:06:09,927 --> 00:06:14,634
So we all walk in here and there's your room and my room, etc.

46
00:06:14,954 --> 00:06:17,057
And with it we have our relationship to it.

47
00:06:19,401 --> 00:06:23,906
So that's the all, that's the all that the Buddha's talking about.

48
00:06:24,966 --> 00:06:37,456
Within that all, there is the whole of samsara, the whole of onward going, the whole of unsatisfactoriness, and within that whole, eventually, is the Nibbanic experience.

49
00:06:38,668 --> 00:06:44,257
So the nirvanic experience isn't outside consciously, we're not going somewhere to experience nirvana.

50
00:06:44,899 --> 00:06:52,831
It's not like you take a train, say, down from Manchester to London, and it's over there.

51
00:06:53,613 --> 00:06:56,577
Nirvana is simply another way of being in the world.

52
00:06:57,139 --> 00:07:05,452
So what we're investigating is the way we're being, or perhaps better, becoming, this constant sense of becoming somebody in the world.

53
00:07:10,764 --> 00:07:25,584
So now, with the sort of Zen Dzogchen approach, that distance between being up in the front of your mind, as it were, and then going out into the world didn't seem so separate.

54
00:07:27,107 --> 00:07:37,379
But in this other tradition, which is the Theravada tradition, and also in the Tibetan tradition known as the Mahamudra tradition, they also have this form of meditation.

55
00:07:39,283 --> 00:07:50,343
We're actually trying to find within ourselves a sort of observation post, a sort of position which is at the interface of consciousness and what the mind is offering, what the senses are offering.

56
00:07:51,084 --> 00:07:55,672
It's as though we've stepped out of ourselves, stood behind it and just watched.

57
00:07:57,074 --> 00:08:00,060
Or above it or below it, it doesn't matter what image you want to use.

58
00:08:00,680 --> 00:08:04,987
But it's as though we are exiting from the personality.

59
00:08:09,759 --> 00:08:10,500
Yeah?

60
00:08:10,521 --> 00:08:15,805
Sort of finding a place where you're up front as to where thoughts arise.

61
00:08:16,666 --> 00:08:17,708
They arise there.

62
00:08:19,870 --> 00:08:25,255
Now, you see, as I'm speaking to you now, I can't be looking at my thoughts that way, or else I'd lose it.

63
00:08:26,076 --> 00:08:31,742
If I become objective to my thoughts, I'll just know thinking, and the talk comes to an end and we'll have to do some walking meditation.

64
00:08:32,342 --> 00:08:33,124
See?

65
00:08:33,144 --> 00:08:34,764
I can't do...

66
00:08:34,784 --> 00:08:39,429
I've got to be up there in the thought.

67
00:08:40,303 --> 00:08:45,089
So it's the same with my emotional life.

68
00:08:45,708 --> 00:08:56,500
If I'm now, say, depressed, you see, and I start feeling my depression, well, it's going to be really depressing for you all, because I'm just going to express how depressed I am.

69
00:08:56,879 --> 00:09:03,687
Somehow, I've got to maintain that distance, but in a sense, when I'm talking, I've got to manufacture.

70
00:09:03,866 --> 00:09:05,568
I've got to manufacture it.

71
00:09:05,548 --> 00:09:33,884
a particular mood to go with the talk i i manufacture a particular mood to go where to go with when i meet somebody i know a happiness arises yeah so but i've got to be up there i've got to be in that emotion as it were whereas here you see i can sort of somehow step behind it i can i can see it i can point to it so i can say joy and it's there as it were in front of me

72
00:09:35,586 --> 00:10:04,648
when we have a pain sort of a headache or something and we're trying to do some work it's there we're sort of in it it's very difficult for us to separate entirely from it and we immediately search for some sort of pills to get rid of it but here I can I can form a sort of space as it were between that which knows the knowing and the headache the knee ache the back ache

73
00:10:05,759 --> 00:10:07,722
The sneeze.

74
00:10:07,783 --> 00:10:12,291
I can see the body going, shoo, like that in front of me.

75
00:10:12,311 --> 00:10:22,289
So there's some way in which I can objectify the whole psychophysical organism that usually I'm in.

76
00:10:22,750 --> 00:10:26,518
I'm in it and being it, walking around the world as this being.

77
00:10:30,193 --> 00:10:34,803
And to do that, we use this little technique, you see, of pointing with a word.

78
00:10:35,203 --> 00:10:36,145
You don't have to do that.

79
00:10:36,246 --> 00:10:41,998
There are perfectly viable vipassana techniques that don't do the pointing with the word, I mean.

80
00:10:42,019 --> 00:10:43,881
But they still get that position.

81
00:10:43,962 --> 00:10:46,126
They still know it as an object.

82
00:10:47,879 --> 00:11:03,052
The reason why the noting is there is, as we discussed last night, just to keep the intellect pointed, but there's a more subtle reason in that even when you are not using a word, you are still conceptualizing what you look at.

83
00:11:03,914 --> 00:11:06,681
You're still seeing it by way of a concept.

84
00:11:08,466 --> 00:11:14,933
So just to say the word, at least as it were, brings that concept to mind, and then we can move towards it.

85
00:11:15,333 --> 00:11:20,139
So one thing might be, you see, is that you might have an itch.

86
00:11:21,360 --> 00:11:24,203
So you recognize it, itching, itching, you see, and you can feel it.

87
00:11:24,663 --> 00:11:25,445
I've got one in here now.

88
00:11:26,326 --> 00:11:33,734
And you feel the itching, you see, and so long as I say itching, there comes that whole response to it.

89
00:11:33,833 --> 00:11:35,975
Got to scratch it, get rid of the itch, you see.

90
00:11:37,288 --> 00:11:55,331
If I can just keep saying itching, but I put my attention directly on to the sensation, it's as though I'm going beyond the idea of itching, and when that idea of itching goes, the idea of reacting to it goes, because I only react to something that I recognise.

91
00:11:55,732 --> 00:12:10,067
When I get down to an itch as an itch, as it really manifests in the body, it's just a little sense disturbance, like a little scratching on the surface of the skin.

92
00:12:10,087 --> 00:12:22,821
And being with that, it means that this awareness I've got, this intelligence I've got, is pulling itself out of its embeddement, confusion with the intellect.

93
00:12:25,770 --> 00:12:35,109
When I was at the college I used to work at, I once went to a colleague who was a sort of, what do you call him, a fundamental materialist.

94
00:12:36,652 --> 00:12:40,418
There is the body, full stop, you know, when you're dead that's the end of it.

95
00:12:40,438 --> 00:12:49,095
And I said to him, is there an intelligence, this is on the corridor, and I said to him, is there an intelligence which doesn't think?

96
00:12:50,559 --> 00:12:52,481
And he sort of looked at me.

97
00:12:52,522 --> 00:12:54,062
We used to have these silly conversations.

98
00:12:54,082 --> 00:12:56,765
And he looked at me, and just for a moment, he sort of looked.

99
00:12:56,785 --> 00:12:57,626
And, you know, he never said it.

100
00:12:57,647 --> 00:12:58,727
He just turned around and walked away.

101
00:13:00,009 --> 00:13:03,192
And I was left with the guy thinking, what the hell have I said, you know?

102
00:13:03,211 --> 00:13:10,078
And he took about 10, 20 paces, stopped, turned around, came straight back at me and said, no, and then walked off.

103
00:13:13,982 --> 00:13:16,585
So presumably he's still stuck in the mire of delusion, you see.

104
00:13:18,808 --> 00:13:25,816
So what we recognise by noting and by seeing thought, by recognising thought, there must be something that recognises the thought.

105
00:13:26,677 --> 00:13:29,438
There must be something outside thought which knows thought.

106
00:13:30,100 --> 00:13:33,383
And then we begin to see that thought is just there.

107
00:13:33,403 --> 00:13:35,004
What do we mean by concept, you see?

108
00:13:35,044 --> 00:13:36,647
What do we mean by concept?

109
00:13:36,667 --> 00:13:37,668
They're symbols, aren't they?

110
00:13:37,868 --> 00:13:39,950
They're just symbols which carry history.

111
00:13:42,392 --> 00:13:45,254
If I say, for instance, ice cream.

112
00:13:45,352 --> 00:13:48,096
You know, I mean, this Freudian sort of, just say ice cream.

113
00:13:48,436 --> 00:13:49,616
What comes immediately, you see?

114
00:13:49,817 --> 00:13:50,878
It's not just the word, is it?

115
00:13:51,739 --> 00:13:55,081
I mean, a cornet came, you know, with a twirl of ice cream.

116
00:13:55,101 --> 00:13:56,903
And then I'm on the beach and there's donkeys.

117
00:13:56,923 --> 00:13:58,845
You see, there's all sorts of things.

118
00:13:58,865 --> 00:14:00,866
Blackpool and stuff.

119
00:14:00,886 --> 00:14:03,389
Like all these things come up just with the word ice cream.

120
00:14:04,110 --> 00:14:08,073
If you said it to me another time, I might get a whole load of different history.

121
00:14:08,894 --> 00:14:10,716
And there comes with it this deliciousness.

122
00:14:11,277 --> 00:14:12,778
See, got to have an ice cream.

123
00:14:17,028 --> 00:14:29,602
So whenever we have a word, we always bring with it our understanding, which is historical, and our emotional involvement in whatever it is that we're conceiving.

124
00:14:30,307 --> 00:14:31,089
And that's okay.

125
00:14:31,188 --> 00:14:31,629
That's okay.

126
00:14:31,649 --> 00:14:33,351
You need it in ordinary life.

127
00:14:33,371 --> 00:14:44,148
But here, you see, in our meditation, we actually want to see that process and how it stops us from directly experiencing what we're actually experiencing.

128
00:14:45,009 --> 00:14:49,655
So, for instance, today we had lasagna.

129
00:14:49,676 --> 00:14:50,115
Am I correct?

130
00:14:50,636 --> 00:14:51,217
I think it was lasagna.

131
00:14:51,238 --> 00:14:51,337
Yeah.

132
00:14:52,346 --> 00:15:03,875
So, you know, there'll be, I'm sure there'll be amongst us, you know, a specialised cook who knows what exactly a lasagne ought to be or whatever, what it should be cooked.

133
00:15:04,361 --> 00:15:07,687
So the pasta was not al dente, you see.

134
00:15:07,726 --> 00:15:09,671
It wasn't quite right.

135
00:15:10,192 --> 00:15:12,634
Teeth should go through it, but there should be a hardness to it.

136
00:15:12,655 --> 00:15:13,716
It shouldn't be too soft.

137
00:15:14,217 --> 00:15:16,621
If there's a little hardness in the middle, it's not properly...

138
00:15:17,043 --> 00:15:25,235
So anybody going there with a concept of what lasagna ought to be like because they are this expert lasagna user, they might not like that at all.

139
00:15:25,375 --> 00:15:28,902
They might have formed a real aversion to it, unable to eat it.

140
00:15:29,100 --> 00:15:30,744
Yeah, you get that with gourmet, don't you?

141
00:15:30,965 --> 00:15:32,628
It's terrible, take it away, I can't stand it.

142
00:15:32,687 --> 00:15:33,990
And it's perfectly good food, you know.

143
00:15:37,256 --> 00:15:42,828
So, as we're eating, we can see how the concept is affecting us.

144
00:15:42,849 --> 00:15:43,590
The chips, you see.

145
00:15:44,371 --> 00:15:46,735
So, while the chips came, I thought, oh, it's lovely, you see.

146
00:15:47,317 --> 00:15:51,024
The chips came, but I had no vinegar, so I could feel this disappointment.

147
00:15:51,730 --> 00:15:53,493
I had salt, but I had no vinegar.

148
00:15:53,793 --> 00:15:54,533
Where's the vinegar?

149
00:15:54,614 --> 00:15:55,755
And I thought, well, relax.

150
00:15:56,998 --> 00:15:57,839
It's not the end of the world.

151
00:15:59,321 --> 00:16:00,261
Chips without vinegar.

152
00:16:00,361 --> 00:16:01,003
No HP.

153
00:16:01,384 --> 00:16:01,663
Terrible.

154
00:16:03,746 --> 00:16:08,975
And this just arises naturally because of my conditioning with chips.

155
00:16:09,455 --> 00:16:10,076
What can you do?

156
00:16:10,135 --> 00:16:13,140
If you battle that, if you think, well, you shouldn't be thinking that.

157
00:16:13,380 --> 00:16:13,761
That's terrible.

158
00:16:14,062 --> 00:16:15,303
That's just suppressive, isn't it?

159
00:16:15,663 --> 00:16:18,629
You're just layering another sort of negativity.

160
00:16:19,048 --> 00:16:21,011
You're layering it with negativity, you see.

161
00:16:23,134 --> 00:16:34,075
So here we are, we're taking this position always behind the mind, if you'll excuse that sort of image, and you're just watching things arise and pass away.

162
00:16:34,095 --> 00:16:36,778
I mean, what is there?

163
00:16:36,799 --> 00:16:44,113
There's sensations, sensations coming from the body, pleasant, unpleasant, feelings from the heart, pleasant, unpleasant, thoughts and images.

164
00:16:46,155 --> 00:16:46,576
That's it.

165
00:16:47,941 --> 00:16:52,825
And it all works in unison with different little habits and it produces this personality.

166
00:16:53,144 --> 00:16:54,787
And the personality changes, doesn't it?

167
00:16:55,606 --> 00:17:01,091
You're this way with this person and then you're slightly different with another person and you're slightly different when you're by yourself.

168
00:17:01,873 --> 00:17:04,174
It's not as though the personality is a static thing.

169
00:17:04,295 --> 00:17:08,679
It's got all sorts of shades and nuances depending on the situation you're in.

170
00:17:09,499 --> 00:17:10,960
Different types of habits arise.

171
00:17:15,023 --> 00:17:17,526
Next time you happen to talk to a policeman, just watch your body.

172
00:17:18,636 --> 00:17:21,059
Or even seeing a policeman as well.

173
00:17:21,080 --> 00:17:21,280
Not me.

174
00:17:23,284 --> 00:17:24,305
All the guilt comes up.

175
00:17:24,444 --> 00:17:24,766
Not me.

176
00:17:24,905 --> 00:17:28,211
I didn't do it.

177
00:17:28,270 --> 00:17:34,299
Or when you're standing next to somebody over whom you have some sort of position.

178
00:17:34,319 --> 00:17:35,781
You just watch your body posture.

179
00:17:36,403 --> 00:17:37,084
You always lift it.

180
00:17:38,586 --> 00:17:39,125
Lift your chin.

181
00:17:40,028 --> 00:17:42,250
Even if the person is six foot six.

182
00:17:43,792 --> 00:17:44,374
Just engage.

183
00:17:45,855 --> 00:17:53,763
And if you walk into a room of somebody whom you sort of have a certain, have to have respect for, even a doctor, you know, very few people have the old respect for doctors.

184
00:17:53,784 --> 00:17:58,509
But even so, walking into a doctor, just notice, you see, you just lower yourself a bit.

185
00:17:59,009 --> 00:18:01,211
But this is just normal body language, you see.

186
00:18:01,811 --> 00:18:06,616
In the West, where we've come to this wonderful state of total equality, of course, we deny all this, you know.

187
00:18:07,196 --> 00:18:10,019
We behave as though we're all perfectly equal, you know.

188
00:18:10,861 --> 00:18:13,723
But in fact, if you watch yourself closely, you change.

189
00:18:13,864 --> 00:18:15,204
You change depending on who you meet.

190
00:18:15,471 --> 00:18:17,075
who you're with.

191
00:18:17,236 --> 00:18:19,881
One of the more obvious ones is when you meet little children.

192
00:18:20,201 --> 00:18:24,430
You suddenly take on this baby voice and act in a stupid way.

193
00:18:25,712 --> 00:18:29,099
The kid thinks there's something wrong with this adult.

194
00:18:29,119 --> 00:18:32,386
As far as you're concerned, you have this special communication with a child.

195
00:18:32,586 --> 00:18:33,970
Hello, how are you doing?

196
00:18:37,695 --> 00:18:44,005
So here we are, taking this position within ourselves, and the process is a detachment.

197
00:18:44,625 --> 00:18:45,646
We're not getting involved.

198
00:18:46,949 --> 00:18:51,694
It's one of allowing things to manifest and watching them die away.

199
00:18:53,136 --> 00:18:54,077
So it's very passive.

200
00:18:54,419 --> 00:18:55,180
It's not active.

201
00:18:55,861 --> 00:18:58,544
We're not actually manufacturing anything in the mind.

202
00:18:59,144 --> 00:19:06,555
What it's leading us to is a stillness of thought, a complete calmness of the heart,

203
00:19:07,395 --> 00:19:08,617
and a stillness of the body.

204
00:19:08,877 --> 00:19:12,503
Silence in the mind, calmness in the heart, stillness in the body.

205
00:19:13,346 --> 00:19:15,249
That's what vipassana would lead you to, you see.

206
00:19:15,269 --> 00:19:23,623
It would lead you to that point of just bringing all that energy, finally just rolling down to this perfect stasis.

207
00:19:24,203 --> 00:19:28,089
Perfect stasis.

208
00:19:28,109 --> 00:19:33,960
Now, if that was it, if that was the end of the plot, you see, then of course that would be the end of the practice.

209
00:19:35,307 --> 00:19:38,791
You would just meditate, come to this end point and that would be it.

210
00:19:40,795 --> 00:19:49,807
Now if you go back to the Buddha's life, so he's struggling to find a way out of his question.

211
00:19:50,288 --> 00:19:51,128
Why do we suffer?

212
00:19:51,209 --> 00:19:52,150
Why are we unhappy?

213
00:19:52,891 --> 00:19:54,713
Why don't we find perfect fulfillment?

214
00:19:55,075 --> 00:19:56,435
Why am I here?

215
00:19:56,557 --> 00:19:59,019
All these existential questions.

216
00:20:02,392 --> 00:20:07,196
And just as an aside, remember that he remembers this point in childhood.

217
00:20:07,518 --> 00:20:09,839
This is really very crucial, very important.

218
00:20:11,582 --> 00:20:22,334
These stories that come through, they give you a pointer as to where the insight about how to go beyond suffering comes.

219
00:20:23,375 --> 00:20:28,240
He's tried all these different methods, the absorptions and the mortifications.

220
00:20:28,901 --> 00:20:32,044
And he comes to this point, he remembers this point in childhood,

221
00:20:32,462 --> 00:20:34,705
where he's watching his father doing the plowing ceremony.

222
00:20:36,047 --> 00:20:54,488
So what is it about that attention that he had there, which is different from all the attention that he'd got through all this practice with these teachers, and through his mortification practices, and it goes back to that mind,

223
00:20:54,721 --> 00:21:16,589
that the child has best recognised sort of before seven, that sort of pre-conceptual, when the mind, before it begins to really proliferate, where you can see, especially young children, where they might see something which they'd never seen before, a bug or something.

224
00:21:16,690 --> 00:21:19,713
I have a picture of two little girls watching this bug and it's perfect.

225
00:21:20,595 --> 00:21:21,977
And they just lock on to it.

226
00:21:22,857 --> 00:21:24,339
It's like the world shuts down

227
00:21:24,521 --> 00:21:26,045
And all they know is this little bug.

228
00:21:26,865 --> 00:21:27,686
And the jaw drops.

229
00:21:27,968 --> 00:21:31,574
Now, that's why in your meditation the jaw has to be relaxed, you see.

230
00:21:32,055 --> 00:21:35,099
Because the jaw and the tongue are intimately connected to thought.

231
00:21:35,500 --> 00:21:39,887
And sometimes you'll actually catch, if you watch, you'll actually catch your tongue moving with thought.

232
00:21:40,910 --> 00:21:43,133
It's already ready to sort of speak, you know.

233
00:21:43,314 --> 00:21:44,875
It's just tickling away on the top.

234
00:21:46,198 --> 00:21:50,125
So by relaxing that, you immediately relax the whole process of thinking.

235
00:21:51,606 --> 00:21:59,257
And after it's actually observed this little bug, you see, only then, when it's absorbed it, when it's really absorbed what it's looking at, will it ask for its name.

236
00:22:00,278 --> 00:22:03,583
And once it's told it's a beetle, it has a concept and a history.

237
00:22:04,604 --> 00:22:10,372
So the next time it sees a beetle, it's much more interested to tell the parent that it recognizes what it is, a beetle.

238
00:22:11,653 --> 00:22:12,855
But it's not seen the beetle.

239
00:22:13,847 --> 00:22:16,251
It's not seeing the beetle like it saw the beetle before.

240
00:22:16,672 --> 00:22:23,321
From now on, all beetles are seen with that history, with that word, with that concept.

241
00:22:23,342 --> 00:22:25,925
Even if the beetle is slightly different, it's still a beetle.

242
00:22:25,965 --> 00:22:26,467
That's a beetle.

243
00:22:27,689 --> 00:22:29,431
That's the end of it.

244
00:22:29,451 --> 00:22:30,311
And that's what we're doing.

245
00:22:30,332 --> 00:22:40,867
We're not specifically seeing what's coming in without the clarity of that historical garbage that comes with everything that we experience.

246
00:22:41,859 --> 00:22:43,982
So here, we're trying to cleanse that.

247
00:22:44,564 --> 00:22:51,213
And that means that we have to go through the process of very gently allowing the mind to calm down, to bring it to a stop.

248
00:22:51,574 --> 00:22:53,195
Calm down, bring it to a stop.

249
00:22:53,217 --> 00:22:58,944
To let these emotions become, to let them express themselves, because that's the emotional history we have.

250
00:22:59,105 --> 00:23:01,808
That's the baggage we're carrying from all the past.

251
00:23:02,789 --> 00:23:06,635
And to allow it to pass away, to burn itself out.

252
00:23:08,084 --> 00:23:12,551
Now, if that were the end of the process, when the Buddha was enlightened, that would have been it, wouldn't it?

253
00:23:12,752 --> 00:23:14,655
He'd have just turned into a sort of blob.

254
00:23:15,478 --> 00:23:17,942
He'd have just sat there and people would have come and said, what's wrong with you, you see?

255
00:23:17,961 --> 00:23:19,003
And he wouldn't be able to speak, would he?

256
00:23:19,104 --> 00:23:21,387
He'd have just said, ugh, or something.

257
00:23:21,429 --> 00:23:23,291
I mean, enlightened, shut up, go away.

258
00:23:23,913 --> 00:23:27,118
So he just sat there and did nothing because he's done it.

259
00:23:27,420 --> 00:23:28,741
See, he's perfectly happy.

260
00:23:29,599 --> 00:23:32,143
But peculiarly enough, that doesn't happen at all.

261
00:23:32,782 --> 00:23:36,487
The first thought, or the first thoughts that arise in his mind is, who?

262
00:23:37,248 --> 00:23:38,388
Who can I teach this to?

263
00:23:39,951 --> 00:23:41,172
Who can I teach this to?

264
00:23:41,192 --> 00:23:44,756
So now we have a very different sort of thing arising.

265
00:23:46,157 --> 00:23:48,380
There must be some connection.

266
00:23:48,440 --> 00:23:55,928
There must be some connection between this wisdom, this intelligence we have, and the world it finds itself in.

267
00:23:56,413 --> 00:24:00,806
the world it finds itself in, and the people that it finds itself connected to.

268
00:24:04,256 --> 00:24:06,161
Now that's put into the Eightfold Path.

269
00:24:06,422 --> 00:24:11,115
So as soon as there is right understanding, there moves into a right attitude.

270
00:24:12,647 --> 00:24:13,869
And it happens naturally.

271
00:24:14,250 --> 00:24:15,733
I mean, we do have exercises.

272
00:24:15,773 --> 00:24:16,955
We do metta practice.

273
00:24:17,798 --> 00:24:22,866
That's a practice on developing goodwill, developing our compassion.

274
00:24:22,886 --> 00:24:26,674
There are all sorts of practices in Buddhism to do that.

275
00:24:27,075 --> 00:24:32,766
But actually, it's not necessary because that wisdom will always want to express itself.

276
00:24:35,394 --> 00:24:38,239
How do we know this wisdom always wants to express itself?

277
00:24:39,079 --> 00:24:47,132
Because this same intelligence, which has now become, shall we say, very wise, when it was deluded, wanted to express itself.

278
00:24:48,314 --> 00:24:56,286
So this intelligence we have, this intuitive intelligence, is always in a state of wanting to express what it knows.

279
00:24:58,409 --> 00:25:03,276
And the reason for that is that it doesn't know what it knows until it's expressed.

280
00:25:04,858 --> 00:25:13,768
If it did not express anything, it would stay in a complete state of original ignorance.

281
00:25:13,788 --> 00:25:17,192
And that's the beginning of the Eightfold Path, the one that we chant in the morning.

282
00:25:17,451 --> 00:25:18,673
Avijja, not knowing.

283
00:25:19,253 --> 00:25:21,936
This ignorance isn't a culpable thing.

284
00:25:21,997 --> 00:25:24,538
It's not as though we're evil because we don't know.

285
00:25:24,558 --> 00:25:26,181
We don't know because we don't know.

286
00:25:26,240 --> 00:25:28,022
So it's like little children.

287
00:25:28,042 --> 00:25:28,643
They don't know.

288
00:25:28,682 --> 00:25:29,584
They have to be taught.

289
00:25:30,986 --> 00:25:33,127
So it's a case of not knowing.

290
00:25:33,749 --> 00:25:39,780
It's the function, it's the inner quality of intelligence that it wants to know.

291
00:25:39,861 --> 00:25:40,942
That's how it's defined.

292
00:25:41,865 --> 00:25:42,685
It wants to know.

293
00:25:42,705 --> 00:25:44,048
Intelligence wants to know.

294
00:25:44,769 --> 00:25:48,416
And in wanting to know, it needs to be able to know it knows.

295
00:25:49,257 --> 00:26:02,173
And it can only know it knows when it expresses something, when it says something, paints something, creates music, talks to people, relates to people, does something in the world, creates something in the world, a business, whatever it is.

296
00:26:02,753 --> 00:26:14,167
Those are all expressions of the either delusive nature in our intelligence or its wisdom nature.

297
00:26:14,923 --> 00:26:18,188
So in other words, you can't exist and not express.

298
00:26:18,909 --> 00:26:20,471
Otherwise you just remain a vegetable.

299
00:26:23,134 --> 00:26:24,317
So there's the Buddha, you see.

300
00:26:24,336 --> 00:26:25,699
He's become fully enlightened.

301
00:26:26,839 --> 00:26:31,346
And he says, I've attained the unconditioned consciousness.

302
00:26:32,647 --> 00:26:33,328
Unconditioned.

303
00:26:34,210 --> 00:26:39,176
Perhaps a better word is unbound, unbounded.

304
00:26:40,337 --> 00:26:47,284
So this intelligence that we have, it's bounded, it's caught up in the sensual world.

305
00:26:47,924 --> 00:26:51,948
So it thinks itself to be what it sees, and the seeing process.

306
00:26:52,689 --> 00:26:59,394
It experiences itself as not only the hearing, but I hear, I am the one who hears.

307
00:27:00,115 --> 00:27:08,303
That binds us to hearing, and it binds us to seeking in hearing the happiness that it craves, right?

308
00:27:09,380 --> 00:27:10,881
I mean, what is suffering?

309
00:27:11,842 --> 00:27:14,183
I don't mean, that's not a definition of suffering.

310
00:27:14,203 --> 00:27:16,006
I mean, what is it that is suffering?

311
00:27:18,126 --> 00:27:19,147
Does the body suffer?

312
00:27:19,548 --> 00:27:22,931
I mean, when you get pain in the knees, is the body suffering?

313
00:27:24,952 --> 00:27:26,253
It's just a sensation, isn't it?

314
00:27:26,855 --> 00:27:29,557
The knee isn't saying, ouch, I'm suffering.

315
00:27:30,458 --> 00:27:33,921
The knee is just giving off certain sensations.

316
00:27:33,941 --> 00:27:38,964
When you're depressed and the depression is there in front of you, is the depression depressed?

317
00:27:39,518 --> 00:27:40,479
about being depressed.

318
00:27:42,321 --> 00:27:45,766
The depression is just a feeling.

319
00:27:45,786 --> 00:27:46,826
It doesn't have any intelligence.

320
00:27:46,846 --> 00:27:47,708
It doesn't know anything.

321
00:27:47,768 --> 00:27:49,931
It's just there as depression.

322
00:27:53,516 --> 00:28:00,243
Does a word, I know, does the word, does the intellect understand what it's actually saying?

323
00:28:04,588 --> 00:28:07,432
Words are just little symbols, aren't they?

324
00:28:07,732 --> 00:28:21,490
So that which understands, that which has a relationship to emotions, that which has a knowledge, understanding of sensations from the body, that is something else, you see.

325
00:28:21,510 --> 00:28:23,134
So it must be that that suffers.

326
00:28:30,644 --> 00:28:34,028
So the answer lies not in the pain of the body,

327
00:28:34,278 --> 00:28:44,551
or in the emotional state of the heart, or in the way the mind thinks, but in the relationship that this intelligence has to the psychophysical organism it finds itself in.

328
00:28:45,394 --> 00:28:47,696
So the relationship we have now is, this is me.

329
00:28:48,817 --> 00:28:57,550
And because of that, we're constantly expecting this to give us that sense of peace and joy, calm, that we want.

330
00:28:58,352 --> 00:28:59,413
And we get upset when it doesn't.

331
00:29:01,336 --> 00:29:02,917
Pain in the knee, you know, and all that sort of stuff.

332
00:29:04,365 --> 00:29:25,377
So, there's an intimate link between the wisdom that we gain from observing ourselves, the purity that we gain from allowing these emotions to expend their energy, and the new attitudes that arise in the heart

333
00:29:25,882 --> 00:29:36,881
which we recognise as sharing, love, giving, generosity, compassion, sympathetic joy, because of that communication we have with other people.

334
00:29:37,882 --> 00:29:46,978
And when that drops further outward, as it were, as an expression, even if you're stuck there with this love, what use is that?

335
00:29:47,278 --> 00:29:51,544
You know, if you went to a cave and just sat there and said, may all beings be happy.

336
00:29:51,743 --> 00:29:52,223
Well, you might.

337
00:29:52,344 --> 00:29:52,884
Of course, you might.

338
00:29:52,944 --> 00:29:54,266
I mean, I'm not being cynical about this.

339
00:29:54,286 --> 00:29:59,172
You might be sending out waves, colossal waves of love with changing the world and all that.

340
00:29:59,192 --> 00:30:05,538
But in a sense, it might also be just you in this cave feeling very happy about how much you love people.

341
00:30:06,318 --> 00:30:07,079
Right?

342
00:30:07,559 --> 00:30:09,782
And if somebody comes along and says, can you help me shift this bowl?

343
00:30:09,803 --> 00:30:10,923
You say, go away.

344
00:30:12,423 --> 00:30:14,707
Don't disturb me, I'm in a state of perfect love here.

345
00:30:17,391 --> 00:30:19,875
So, you can get stuck at these stages.

346
00:30:19,894 --> 00:30:26,246
You might think, well, the whole purpose of life is just to sit and meditate and get into this perfect state of peace and happiness, you see.

347
00:30:26,506 --> 00:30:28,108
But that's not what the Buddha did.

348
00:30:28,829 --> 00:30:31,815
Remember that he's the exemplar, he's the paradigm of our path.

349
00:30:33,060 --> 00:30:40,178
And you might think, well, in that case, I might stop that attitude and just develop this huge compassion, the Buddha heart.

350
00:30:40,719 --> 00:30:48,717
But that just turns you into just a self-regarding person.

351
00:30:48,738 --> 00:30:51,103
You just sit there beaming out this love.

352
00:30:51,893 --> 00:30:59,644
So it has to move out, it has to express itself, and it expresses itself through right speech, right action, and right livelihood.

353
00:31:00,163 --> 00:31:04,109
So you can see how the Eightfold Path just follows, follows the one after the other.

354
00:31:04,830 --> 00:31:21,073
So the way we speak, the way we communicate is an expression of that heart, the kindness, compassionate way, sympathy, joyfulness, which is an expression of our understanding, of the way we relate to the world.

355
00:31:22,183 --> 00:31:30,299
When we start doing something, it's done with that attention because that's what this intelligence is.

356
00:31:30,339 --> 00:31:31,863
It's a state of attention.

357
00:31:32,324 --> 00:31:37,674
And that's a nice word in English because there's also the word attend, to attend to.

358
00:31:37,694 --> 00:31:41,863
Nurses attend to their patients.

359
00:31:43,462 --> 00:31:50,611
There's a sense of, in that word, there's almost an inclusive, the idea of caring, attention and care, care and attention.

360
00:31:51,032 --> 00:31:53,742
So you could say that those are the hallmarks of your daily life.

361
00:31:54,769 --> 00:31:59,598
There are some things that you have to pay more attention to, like a phone call.

362
00:31:59,618 --> 00:32:03,645
And there are some things that you have to be more careful with, like when you're cooking.

363
00:32:03,767 --> 00:32:04,228
Be careful.

364
00:32:04,969 --> 00:32:10,618
So the two are one and the same, but they're coming from, shall we say, a different type of relationship.

365
00:32:10,720 --> 00:32:16,390
One is more based on the intellect, the understanding, and one is more based in the heart, on a sense of care.

366
00:32:17,382 --> 00:32:44,757
they're always there you see so now you can see how this in how this intelligence which has which we've um training to sit back and watch to sit back and watch and understand and see and understand what's going on how it now begins to as it were come down into the attitude into the heart and how it begins to flow outward into the world in the way we speak and the way we act and finally the very livelihood that we have

367
00:32:47,082 --> 00:32:49,223
So here's the Buddha putting livelihood.

368
00:32:49,644 --> 00:32:53,709
Logically speaking, there's no need to put livelihood there because it's included in right action.

369
00:32:54,630 --> 00:33:06,061
But such is his understanding of the fact that most of our lives are doing something, unless we're unfortunate not to have a job.

370
00:33:06,982 --> 00:33:09,605
But even then, in the West anyway, they come and go.

371
00:33:09,645 --> 00:33:12,228
So now, your attitude.

372
00:33:12,288 --> 00:33:14,810
What is your attitude to the work you're doing?

373
00:33:15,397 --> 00:33:45,287
what is the attitude to the work you're doing yesterday I was talking to somebody who was going through one of these awful periods where you know there's that sort of vanity about what they're doing about the uselessness why am I doing this it means nothing to me and all that sort of stuff and what you often find when you get into that mood is that actually it's coming again from this idea of self that all we're concerned about is making the job interesting to me

374
00:33:46,313 --> 00:33:47,755
It's interesting to me.

375
00:33:48,174 --> 00:33:49,537
What's it for me?

376
00:33:49,696 --> 00:33:51,940
How much am I burning?

377
00:33:53,102 --> 00:34:00,029
And there's always going to arise that sort of dissatisfaction because the I always wants to aggrandize.

378
00:34:00,109 --> 00:34:01,471
That's the self.

379
00:34:01,491 --> 00:34:02,993
It always wants to accumulate.

380
00:34:03,335 --> 00:34:05,596
Because the more it accumulates, the safer it feels.

381
00:34:06,377 --> 00:34:10,483
I mean, you feel much safer if you had a million pounds in the bank than just a hundred.

382
00:34:11,083 --> 00:34:11,364
I would.

383
00:34:12,266 --> 00:34:15,510
I mean, you'd have this fallback, you see.

384
00:34:15,489 --> 00:34:27,106
So, I can't remember, there was, I think, one of these rich people said, I did poverty, I've done poverty, and I've done riches, and being rich is better.

385
00:34:28,309 --> 00:34:35,440
So, there's no particular, there's no particular, as we say, virtue in being poor, it's just the way you end up.

386
00:34:37,427 --> 00:34:43,733
But you can see how the self is always trying to make the world safe and wonderful around itself.

387
00:34:44,074 --> 00:34:48,637
So what's missing, you see, is missing that connection with the other person.

388
00:34:48,657 --> 00:34:51,940
So again, as soon as we do that, people become objects.

389
00:34:52,460 --> 00:34:55,623
You're just using them, using them to fulfill your desires.

390
00:34:56,523 --> 00:35:02,208
And that's bound to bring a dissatisfaction because people refuse to be objects to your desire.

391
00:35:02,309 --> 00:35:04,471
They always do something which you don't want them to do.

392
00:35:05,391 --> 00:35:07,333
And then you get angry and say, why did you do that?

393
00:35:09,996 --> 00:35:14,387
If we now turn around in ourselves and we say, right, well...

394
00:35:14,958 --> 00:35:17,661
What would be a proper attitude to my work, you see?

395
00:35:17,802 --> 00:35:20,045
Well, there has to be, obviously, some self-care.

396
00:35:20,465 --> 00:35:31,342
So we've tried to make that distinction with our eating, that we're not eating just to gain happiness, just to feel sort of blissed out on chips.

397
00:35:31,983 --> 00:35:32,643
We're not doing that.

398
00:35:33,684 --> 00:35:41,215
We're actually trying to feed the body, we're trying to change our relationship to food, seeing it as medicine, seeing it as nourishment.

399
00:35:41,235 --> 00:35:43,800
That gives us a very different attitude, you see.

400
00:35:44,286 --> 00:35:53,860
So now, when I'm doing my work, when we're doing work in society, surely the attitude which I ought to give out is one of service, isn't it?

401
00:35:54,521 --> 00:35:55,623
Service.

402
00:35:55,643 --> 00:36:04,295
As soon as you serve other people, you're immediately in a state of communication to them as people, because you're trying to be of service to them.

403
00:36:05,115 --> 00:36:10,563
So to be of service to somebody means that you have to open up to them as individuals.

404
00:36:10,780 --> 00:36:11,701
They have to speak to you.

405
00:36:11,721 --> 00:36:13,041
They have to tell you what they want.

406
00:36:13,422 --> 00:36:16,385
Even if it's just brushing the streets, for heaven's sake.

407
00:36:17,025 --> 00:36:18,746
You're doing it as a service.

408
00:36:19,228 --> 00:36:22,150
So this puts a very different timbre on life, doesn't it?

409
00:36:22,170 --> 00:36:23,931
It puts a very different shading on life.

410
00:36:25,813 --> 00:36:29,036
I mean, we do it naturally with people whom we love, with family members.

411
00:36:29,097 --> 00:36:33,121
We'll do things for them and do it with a good heart and with an open heart.

412
00:36:34,422 --> 00:36:37,384
And when you do that, you get that good feeling, don't you?

413
00:36:37,403 --> 00:36:39,065
You get that glow, you see?

414
00:36:40,025 --> 00:36:42,751
So that's the attitude of livelihood.

415
00:36:43,152 --> 00:36:46,481
It's one of being of service, you see.

416
00:36:47,565 --> 00:36:51,436
That doesn't take away the fact that there has to be that self-regard as well.

417
00:36:51,456 --> 00:36:54,202
You have to do something which is good for you, good for them.

418
00:36:56,831 --> 00:37:22,501
So in this way you can see how the meditation is preparing us to develop a completely different, not completely, I'm sure you all have this sense of service, is to develop the attitude of service and to distinguish between doing something just simply for ourselves out of selfish motivations and doing something which is caring for us, caring for the other.

419
00:37:40,436 --> 00:37:48,286
And that brings us into that sort of funny area where people get stuck, where they say, well, should I go for a position?

420
00:37:48,827 --> 00:37:50,148
Where does ambition come in?

421
00:37:50,789 --> 00:37:58,577
Should I then just say, well, I want to serve society, I want to serve people, and I'll just wait for the job to come.

422
00:37:59,099 --> 00:38:00,719
And you end up on the dole.

423
00:38:03,943 --> 00:38:09,010
Again, it's always, if you're serving, if you're serving,

424
00:38:09,766 --> 00:38:11,489
What you want to serve is your best, isn't it?

425
00:38:11,548 --> 00:38:16,818
If you invite a person round for a meal, you want to serve the best food that you can make, don't you?

426
00:38:16,978 --> 00:38:18,039
You want to serve them the best.

427
00:38:18,360 --> 00:38:20,264
You want to offer what you have as the best.

428
00:38:21,184 --> 00:38:25,713
If you invite a friend round for beans on toast, it can be depressing.

429
00:38:28,097 --> 00:38:29,478
Unless you told them, of course.

430
00:38:32,362 --> 00:38:37,329
So when you offer your services to society, you see, you're offering your best.

431
00:38:37,690 --> 00:38:44,820
So if there's an opening which you feel you can do, you see, then you go and offer your service to that.

432
00:38:47,364 --> 00:39:00,985
If you don't get the job you want, if you don't get the position you wanted, because you did it out of an attitude of service, in other words, there's an acceptance that you don't fit into what they want, then there's no pain, there's no hurt.

433
00:39:01,791 --> 00:39:04,875
The potential to do that job still lies there.

434
00:39:05,396 --> 00:39:08,378
It's just they either found somebody else or whatever.

435
00:39:08,898 --> 00:39:15,987
We had a case just recently at Gaia House where somebody came to apply for a job, one of the managers' jobs.

436
00:39:16,007 --> 00:39:17,789
And we knew her.

437
00:39:17,849 --> 00:39:20,550
She was a fairly regular visitor.

438
00:39:21,351 --> 00:39:25,456
And she'd set herself, set her heart on becoming a manager, you see.

439
00:39:27,318 --> 00:39:31,663
But there was another person who applied for the same position.

440
00:39:32,014 --> 00:39:34,318
And eventually it was this other person who got the job.

441
00:39:35,079 --> 00:39:37,103
Well, it was like a disaster, really.

442
00:39:40,608 --> 00:39:42,152
Weeping, despair.

443
00:39:43,132 --> 00:39:45,115
And it was only a year's job.

444
00:39:45,197 --> 00:39:48,802
I mean, you'd be out after a year.

445
00:39:49,023 --> 00:39:51,686
There wasn't some sort of huge life commitment to it.

446
00:39:52,427 --> 00:39:58,257
But the suffering that she went through because of that belies that

447
00:39:59,014 --> 00:40:05,204
Even though there was that wanting to serve, there was something else there which attached her to that job.

448
00:40:05,686 --> 00:40:08,070
And not getting it brought about the pain.

449
00:40:11,436 --> 00:40:21,932
So it's a case of offering ourselves as a service and then recognizing that it might not be received, it might not be accepted.

450
00:40:22,052 --> 00:40:22,795
And that's okay.

451
00:40:23,536 --> 00:40:24,297
That's okay.

452
00:40:25,474 --> 00:40:28,742
So it doesn't stop you from following an ambitious route.

453
00:40:33,172 --> 00:40:41,172
There's nothing stopping any of you becoming Prime Minister if you feel that's where your talent lies.

454
00:40:48,340 --> 00:40:54,737
So I hope that makes a sort of connection between what we're doing here in the sitting and your daily life.

455
00:40:54,757 --> 00:40:57,666
I hope it sort of makes you connect, you see.

456
00:41:00,755 --> 00:41:03,463
There's a very intimate connection to it, very intimate.

457
00:41:10,936 --> 00:41:19,327
So to reinforce that, you have to take some of the tricks that you gain from your meditation retreat into your daily life.

458
00:41:19,987 --> 00:41:22,570
And one of the most powerful ones is to stop.

459
00:41:23,152 --> 00:41:23,793
Keep stopping.

460
00:41:25,355 --> 00:41:29,721
Very simple, very simple occasions like, you know, if the phone rings.

461
00:41:29,880 --> 00:41:34,686
So when you get the first ring, you don't have to launch yourself at the phone, do you?

462
00:41:34,706 --> 00:41:37,550
I mean, you know, you can note that the phone is ringing.

463
00:41:37,969 --> 00:41:39,139
And just relax, you know.

464
00:41:39,159 --> 00:41:41,195
Like most people will hold on for three rings.

465
00:41:41,918 --> 00:41:44,460
I hold on for seven, ten rings for heaven's sake.

466
00:41:44,481 --> 00:41:46,362
I'm very patient.

467
00:41:46,382 --> 00:41:47,603
Well, three rings at least.

468
00:41:48,585 --> 00:41:53,510
So there's just that recognition, the phone is ringing, and then you just finish off what you're doing.

469
00:41:53,570 --> 00:41:56,733
You don't just forget, and then when you come back, you've lost your place.

470
00:41:57,634 --> 00:42:03,699
Then the next one goes, and you pick it up on the third ring.

471
00:42:04,059 --> 00:42:09,545
You're calm, you're collected, you're not in a rush, and therefore you're open to the telephone call.

472
00:42:14,976 --> 00:42:25,393
After you've, you know, when you set yourself a task at work or just in your daily life, you see, if you're aware of that intention, then put an end time to that intention.

473
00:42:27,996 --> 00:42:34,246
Like, for instance, you know, I mess around a lot with this crazy computer stuff.

474
00:42:34,266 --> 00:42:38,773
And if I don't put a time on it, like two hours passes.

475
00:42:38,793 --> 00:42:40,474
I'm sure you've all experienced that.

476
00:42:41,277 --> 00:42:42,878
You wake up and two hours are gone.

477
00:42:42,898 --> 00:42:43,599
Two and a half hours.

478
00:42:44,041 --> 00:42:44,240
Whoa!

479
00:42:45,588 --> 00:42:51,659
And I've got in the habit, I have this little watch here which gives me a beep every 40 minutes.

480
00:42:52,340 --> 00:42:54,724
So just stop for a minute, you know.

481
00:42:54,744 --> 00:42:58,791
It stops you getting caught up in something, you see.

482
00:43:00,012 --> 00:43:06,184
So when you set yourself a job, no matter what it is, it doesn't matter of length, you see, you could be just mowing the lawn.

483
00:43:06,925 --> 00:43:09,269
So you say to yourself at the end of that, I'll just stop.

484
00:43:09,610 --> 00:43:10,532
You just relax.

485
00:43:12,588 --> 00:43:26,563
And then the accumulation of that job, maybe you got a bit of an irritation, who knows, you know, maybe you picked up some sort of, maybe you developed unwittingly some sort of irritation around it, some sort of rush, some sort of pressure.

486
00:43:29,505 --> 00:43:34,050
Just stop, let it, let it.

487
00:43:34,070 --> 00:43:41,599
And in this way, throughout the day, we're constantly bringing ourselves back to this very posture, this posture of just being here, you see.

488
00:43:43,942 --> 00:44:01,748
then you move again from that base and for those of you who haven't done this before it's important to do meditation in the morning and evening

489
00:44:04,376 --> 00:44:05,257
Two hours is good.

490
00:44:06,460 --> 00:44:09,023
But 20 minutes is enough.

491
00:44:10,003 --> 00:44:13,648
You just need enough time to access this level of consciousness.

492
00:44:13,929 --> 00:44:15,231
It's a level of consciousness.

493
00:44:15,791 --> 00:44:16,913
A way of being in the world.

494
00:44:17,753 --> 00:44:20,958
Just remind yourself, this is where I'm supposed to be at all day.

495
00:44:21,858 --> 00:44:24,822
And then throughout the day you do these little stoppings.

496
00:44:24,882 --> 00:44:26,105
Keep bringing yourself back.

497
00:44:26,525 --> 00:44:28,266
Remember how it was in that sitting.

498
00:44:30,590 --> 00:44:32,713
And then in the evening when you come back,

499
00:44:32,862 --> 00:44:36,867
Always better before you eat, you see, before you have an evening ahead of you.

500
00:44:37,407 --> 00:44:41,753
Just to sit for 20 minutes and just see what you've accumulated during the day.

501
00:44:42,614 --> 00:44:45,679
The tensions, the irritations, the disappointment.

502
00:44:46,659 --> 00:44:48,262
Just let them calm down, calm down.

503
00:44:48,541 --> 00:44:50,585
And of course it makes your evening much more pleasant.

504
00:44:51,827 --> 00:44:53,289
If you do it too late, you just fall asleep.

505
00:44:54,170 --> 00:44:58,755
If you do it just before you go to bed, it's just preparation for falling asleep really.

506
00:44:59,135 --> 00:44:59,697
Nothing happens.

507
00:45:00,367 --> 00:45:03,572
So do it when you're still awake, especially before you eat.

508
00:45:04,092 --> 00:45:06,275
And then you'll see it has an effect on the evening.

509
00:45:07,557 --> 00:45:09,320
So just very slowly, very slowly.

510
00:45:11,402 --> 00:45:17,291
And after each of these meditations, just a moment of developing metta, goodwill you see, which we'll do tomorrow.

511
00:45:18,411 --> 00:45:22,797
And that prepares this intelligence to move into the world with a proper attitude.

512
00:45:28,027 --> 00:45:32,755
So that's the path in a nutshell, so we say.

